TidyTuesday - Week 5

Week 5 of TidyTuesday.

Descriptive analysis

1. What is the mean income for each state?

names(df)
 [1] "CensusId"        "State"           "County"          "TotalPop"       
 [5] "Men"             "Women"           "Hispanic"        "White"          
 [9] "Black"           "Native"          "Asian"           "Pacific"        
[13] "Citizen"         "Income"          "IncomeErr"       "IncomePerCap"   
[17] "IncomePerCapErr" "Poverty"         "ChildPoverty"    "Professional"   
[21] "Service"         "Office"          "Construction"    "Production"     
[25] "Drive"           "Carpool"         "Transit"         "Walk"           
[29] "OtherTransp"     "WorkAtHome"      "MeanCommute"     "Employed"       
[33] "PrivateWork"     "PublicWork"      "SelfEmployed"    "FamilyWork"     
[37] "Unemployment"   
df %>% 
  select(State, Income) %>% 
  group_by(State) %>% 
  summarise(Av_income = mean(Income))

Plot this out

df %>% 
  select(State, Income) %>% 
  group_by(State) %>% 
  summarise(Median_income = mean(Income)) %>% 
  arrange(Median_income) %>% 
  mutate(State = forcats::as_factor(State)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(State, Median_income)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()

Look at Pennsylvania

Get the median incomes for each state in PA

df %>% 
  filter(State == "Pennsylvania") %>% 
  select(County, Income) %>% 
  arrange(Income) %>% 
  mutate(County = forcats::as_factor(County)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(County, Income)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()
